## 📊 1. Understanding the Data Distribution  

### Figure 1: Distribution of Product Ratings  
Most products have ratings concentrated between 4.0 and 4.6, indicating generally positive customer feedback.

![Distribution of Ratings](images/fig1_ratings_distribution.png)

**Insight:**  
Ratings alone are not enough to differentiate products due to limited variation.

---

### Figure 2: Distribution of Product Prices  
The majority of products fall within lower price ranges, with fewer premium-priced items.

![Distribution of Prices](images/fig2_price_distribution.png)

**Insight:**  
The platform primarily targets mass-market consumers, with a smaller premium segment.

---

## 🏷️ 2. Market Structure & Brand Analysis  

### Figure 3: Top 15 Brands by Number of Products  
A small number of brands dominate the platform in terms of product listings.

![Top Brands](images/fig3_top_brands.png)

**Insight:**  
The market shows a **Pareto effect**, where a few brands control a large share of products.

---

## ⭐ 3. Customer Behavior & Engagement  

### Figure 4: Review Count vs Rating (Log Scale)  
Products with higher review counts tend to have more stable ratings.

![Review vs Rating](images/fig4_review_vs_rating.png)

**Insight:**  
Customer engagement (review volume) increases rating reliability and trust.

---

## 🔗 4. Feature Relationships  

### Figure 5: Correlation Heatmap  
Strong relationships exist between rating count and review count, while discount shows weak correlation.

![Correlation Heatmap](images/fig5_correlation.png)

**Insight:**  
Engagement metrics are more important than pricing variables in explaining product performance.

---

## 💬 5. Customer Feedback Analysis  

### Figure 6: Word Cloud of Negative Reviews  
Frequently occurring words include "shade", "match", and "dark".

![Word Cloud](images/fig6_wordcloud.png)

**Insight:**  
Shade mismatch is a major issue for customers when purchasing cosmetics online.

